<p></p>:
The requirement for this website came to my attention via Gumtree. The client required a website that would show their graphic and illustration skills. The domain name was already owned by the client and was being directed to a blog.

\

The client had hand drawn the home page of the website. I used this as a template for the website. Then all I had to do was add the content. Also, a shop was required for the client to sell items. This was done via PayPal. When the user wishes to purchase an item, they are taken to a external PayPal website.

\

She also wanted to have two galleries on the website. These galleries would need to be updated without FTP and coding. I was able to do this by integrating a Flickr applet into the website.

\

The website went live March 2010.

\

Programs used: Adobe Photoshop, Dreamweaver
Languages used: XHTML, CSS, PHP, JavaScript

This particular client required a portfolio website that showed off their architecture work. The website had already been designed, and I was required to convert it from a Photoshop file to be ready for the internet.

\

This required slicing the images from the PSD file, then using XHTML, CSS and JavaScript to implement the website. There was constant contact between myself and the client during the construction stage.

\

Using Adobe Flash, I created a slideshow for the home page.

\

The website went live January 2010.

\

Programs used: Adobe Flash, Photoshop, Dreamweaver
Languages used: XHTML, CSS, PHP, JavaScript

This project came to my attention via Manchester Student Volunteers.

\

The client required a website that was simple, and allowed her to edit the pages with ease, as she had no programming experience. The website was created in CSS stylesheets, XHTML and using div tags, rather than using a table base. Adobe Dreamweaver was used to develop the website, while Adobe Flash was used to create the animated banner on the home page.

\

Lightbox 2 was used on the multimedia page to add a different dimension to the user's image viewing experience.

\

The website allows the client to edit the pages however they wish. There is no FTP or coding involved. The client simply logs in to the Adobe InContext Editing section by pressing CTRL + E on the keyboard, on the selected page that they wish to edit.

\

The client also wished that any e-mail that was associated with this website, be online based, and allow her to add and remove any e-mail addresses as she wished. This was done using Google mail.

\

Programs used: Adobe Flash, Photoshop, Dreamweaver
Languages used: XHTML, CSS, PHP, JavaScript

Sneezing activates the same parts of the brain as an orgasm. It gives pleasure when it's fully consummated. Unfortunately frustration is around the corner. An incomplete sneeze triggers a feeling of non-consummation which - as well as sexual dissatisfaction - can lead to physio-psychological disorders. If in the sexual sphere auto-erotism and sex toys have saved generations of unsatisfied and irritable women, would-be sneezers await for answers from scientists and sociotherapists yet. How can their pain be relieved? While the scientific community is dealing with the 'incomplete sneeze' problem, other social and political factors are affecting the life of our 'ah ah ah without choo' peers. Unemployment, precarious work, credit crunch, the Conservatives&LiberalDemocrats coalition and Cheryl Cole's new hair dye make things even worse.  A new movement of unsatisfied sneezers was established recently in Newport thanks to the support of the local Union of Mineworkers. The movement is growing and is likely to spread like wildfire in the short term. 
Sneezers of the world, unite! Hoist your tissue and free yourself!
